An example
Suppose that we have a population of children, with the ages of the children distributed uniformly, in the population. The height of a child will be stochastically related to the age: e.g. when we know that a child is of age 7, this influences the chance of the child being 1.5 meters tall. We could formalize that relationship in a linear regression model, like this: 
heighti = b0 + b1agei + Œµi, where b0 is the intercept, b1 is a parameter that age is multiplied by to obtain a prediction of height, Œµi is the error term, and i identifies the child. This implies that height is predicted by age, with some error.
An admissible model must be consistent with all the data points.  Thus, a straight line (heighti = b0 + b1agei) cannot be the equation for a model of the data‚Äîunless it exactly fits all the data points, i.e. all the data points lie perfectly on the line.  The error term, Œµi, must be included in the equation, so that the model is consistent with all the data points.
To do statistical inference, we would first need to assume some probability distributions for the Œµi.  For instance, we might assume that the Œµi distributions are i.i.d. Gaussian, with zero mean.  In this instance, the model would have 3 parameters: b0, b1, and the variance of the Gaussian distribution.
We can formally specify the model in the form (
  
    
      
